00:19.936 --> 00:24.148
<i>Heaven, I'm in heaven</i>

00:25.316 --> 00:30.154
<i>And my heart beats
so that I can hardly speak</i>

00:31.698 --> 00:36.452
<i>And I seem to find the happiness I seek</i>

00:37.996 --> 00:43.125
<i>When we're out together
dancing cheek to cheek</i>

00:45.170 --> 00:49.131
<i>Heaven, I'm in heaven</i>

00:50.759 --> 00:56.305
<i>And the cares that hung
around me through the week</i>

00:57.140 --> 01:01.602
<i>Seem to vanish like a gambler's lucky streak</i>

01:03.438 --> 01:08.400
<i>When we're out together
dancing cheek to cheek</i>

01:09.903 --> 01:13.155
<i>Oh, I love to climb a mountain</i>

01:13.198 --> 01:16.366
<i>And to reach the highest peak</i>

01:16.451 --> 01:20.079
<i>But it doesn't thrill me half as much</i>

01:20.163 --> 01:22.706
<i>As dancing cheek to cheek</i>

01:22.791 --> 01:25.876
<i>Oh, I love to go out fishing</i>

01:25.960 --> 01:29.004
<i>In a river or a creek</i>

01:29.089 --> 01:32.716
<i>But I don't enjoy it half as much</i>

01:32.842 --> 01:35.969
<i>As dancing cheek to cheek</i>

01:36.012 --> 01:38.263
<i>Dance with me</i>

01:38.348 --> 01:41.517
<i>I want my arm about you</i>

01:41.559 --> 01:44.895
<i>The charm about you</i>

01:44.979 --> 01:50.818
<i>Will carry me through to heaven</i>

01:51.528 --> 01:54.530
<i>I'm in heaven</i>

01:54.572 --> 01:56.073
<i>And my heart...</i>

01:56.157 --> 01:57.324
(CLANKING)

01:57.367 --> 02:00.202
Oh, Cecilia, be careful. Are you all right?

02:00.286 --> 02:01.703
CECILIA: Yes.

02:01.788 --> 02:04.039
You're gonna like this one.
It's better than last week.

02:04.124 --> 02:05.916
It's more romantic.

02:06.543 --> 02:09.461
Miss, I wanted
oatmeal before my scrambled eggs.

02:09.920 --> 02:11.797
Oh, sorry, I'll get it right away. Sorry.

02:11.881 --> 02:13.465
MAN: Can I get cereal, too, and a doughnut.

02:13.550 --> 02:15.259
Oh, cereal and a doughnut, right.

02:15.343 --> 02:17.511
Listen, there's a new movie at the Jewel
starting tonight.

02:17.554 --> 02:19.263
I didn't even get to see last week's.

02:19.347 --> 02:21.390
Oh, you missed it? It was wonderful.

02:21.474 --> 02:23.934
I love Jane Froman,
and James Melton plays...

02:24.018 --> 02:26.645
First he's a hotel
porter and then he becomes a radio singer

02:26.729 --> 02:28.647
and then he becomes an opera singer.

02:28.731 --> 02:30.691
The music was just beautiful.

02:30.733 --> 02:33.402
You know the one
that I like is, <i>Okay, America!</i>

02:33.486 --> 02:36.405
Oh, yeah, I saw that twice. That was great,

02:36.447 --> 02:38.490
when she threatens to kill Lew Ayres...

02:38.575 --> 02:40.909
I love Lew Ayres' looks.
Do you think he's married?

02:40.952 --> 02:42.911
Is he married? Are you crazy?

02:42.996 --> 02:45.372
Yes, he's married to Ginger Rogers.

02:45.415 --> 02:49.042
God. They got married
on a boat off the island of Catalina.

02:49.085 --> 02:51.837
They live in Beverly Hills
and sometimes holiday in Spain.

02:51.921 --> 02:55.549
He used to be married to Lola Lane,
but Ginger's better for him.

02:55.592 --> 02:56.675
- She's so lovely.
- MAN: Where's my toast?

02:56.759 --> 02:58.552
Oh. Coming right up, one second.

02:58.595 --> 03:00.762
- Ginger used to be married to Jack...
- BOSS: Let's go, girls.

03:00.847 --> 03:02.598
- Let's go, Cecilia.
- Sorry.

03:02.682 --> 03:05.684
- Your sister is slow.
- But she's still learning.

03:05.768 --> 03:07.728
Ladies, there's a depression on.

03:07.770 --> 03:09.396
There are a lot of
other people who would like this job

03:09.439 --> 03:11.440
- if you can't handle it.
- No, I can handle it.

03:11.482 --> 03:13.233
It's okay.

03:13.276 --> 03:15.027
Ginger used
to be married to Jack Culpepper,

03:15.111 --> 03:17.863
who I think took out
Ruth Chatterton before she married George

03:17.947 --> 03:19.531
- (PLATE BREAKING)
- Oh, I...

03:19.616 --> 03:21.158
BOSS: Look,
that's the second one this week.

03:21.242 --> 03:22.993
I'm sorry. I'll pick it all up.

03:23.077 --> 03:24.786
Come on, Cecilia, shape up.

03:27.123 --> 03:29.458
Hand them on. Now, for three pennies.

03:34.964 --> 03:36.256
(EXCLAIMS)

03:37.258 --> 03:39.468
MAN: Hey, Monk. Here comes your wife.

03:42.597 --> 03:45.307
Boy, am I glad to see you.
You got any dough?

03:45.391 --> 03:48.018
Oh, tips weren't so good today.

03:48.102 --> 03:49.394
Come on, give me something. I'm busted.

03:49.479 --> 03:53.357
Hmm. I hear there's some jobs
opening up over at the ice factory.

03:53.858 --> 03:55.400
- No, there's nothing. I was there.
- Yeah?

03:55.485 --> 03:56.568
Yeah, I was there. All right?

03:56.653 --> 03:59.154
Harriet Rufus
says all you guys do all day is just

03:59.197 --> 04:02.699
pitch pennies
and make passes at the girls who walk by.

04:02.784 --> 04:04.493
Well, Harriet Rufus is a douche bag.

04:04.535 --> 04:07.537
Listen, I got to save
the rest for groceries and stuff, okay?

04:07.622 --> 04:09.748
Yeah, okay, yeah, right. You got it?

04:09.832 --> 04:10.916
What are you doing here?

04:11.000 --> 04:12.459
Oh, you want to go to the movies tonight?

04:12.502 --> 04:13.669
There's an early show.

04:13.753 --> 04:14.962
- I can't, I can't.
- How come?

04:15.004 --> 04:17.130
- Well, the guys are coming over tonight.
- Again?

04:17.214 --> 04:18.757
What, you don't like it?

04:18.841 --> 04:22.803
Well, all you do is you drink and play dice,

04:22.845 --> 04:24.346
and I wind up getting smacked.

04:24.430 --> 04:26.348
Well, I got to get even, don't I?

04:26.391 --> 04:27.599
I owe everybody in town.

04:27.684 --> 04:30.852
You're never home anymore
except to play dice and cards.

04:30.937 --> 04:34.856
Meanwhile, I gotta take in extra laundry
after work to pay the rent.

04:34.983 --> 04:37.359
Well, what do you want?
Did I close the factory?

04:37.402 --> 04:39.027
You didn't used to be like this, Monk.

04:39.112 --> 04:40.696
Well, I got a lot on my mind.

04:40.780 --> 04:43.407
You think I like scratching around for work?

04:43.491 --> 04:44.700
Living like a bum the last two years?

04:44.784 --> 04:47.577
I don't know how much
longer I can go on like this, you know.

04:47.662 --> 04:49.288
Listen, the country
will get back working again.

04:49.372 --> 04:51.665
- Things are bound to get better. I promise.
- Yeah.

04:51.708 --> 04:53.542
You know I'm crazy about you, huh?

04:53.584 --> 04:55.877
You never pay any attention to me anymore.

04:55.920 --> 04:58.547
That's why I thought
if we could go to the movies tonight,

04:58.589 --> 05:00.299
you know,
you could forget your troubles a little.

05:00.383 --> 05:01.425
Yeah, yeah, forget my troubles.

05:01.509 --> 05:04.928
Cecilia, you like
sitting through that junk, okay?

05:05.013 --> 05:07.180
- I'm gonna shoot crap, okay?
- Tsk.

05:07.223 --> 05:09.266
Go to the movie by yourself.

05:09.350 --> 05:11.351
You make passes at the girls who go by?

05:11.394 --> 05:13.020
Hey, look, you're not my boss.

05:13.062 --> 05:14.229
And don't give me that look.

05:14.314 --> 05:15.397
You'd think I was a criminal.

05:15.523 --> 05:18.483
Come on, give us a hug, just one, come on.

05:18.568 --> 05:20.360
All right? Good.

05:20.403 --> 05:23.822
And don't come home late.
I worry. All right?

05:24.615 --> 05:26.033
See you later.

05:29.579 --> 05:30.996
(CLAPPING) Let's go.

05:38.629 --> 05:40.047
Two, please.

05:42.133 --> 05:43.216
Two.

05:45.094 --> 05:47.095
Just one tonight, please, Doris.

05:48.014 --> 05:49.056
Thank you.

05:53.311 --> 05:54.311
Evening, Mr. Ruskin.

06:00.234 --> 06:01.777
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

06:46.114 --> 06:47.489
<i>Jason, I'm bored.</i>

06:48.533 --> 06:51.159
<i>I'm bored with cocktail parties
and opening nights.</i>

06:51.869 --> 06:54.830
<i>I'm bored with evenings at the Opera
and weekends at the races.</i>

06:54.872 --> 06:56.832
<i>A few days in Paris might be just the thing</i>

06:56.874 --> 06:58.667
<i>to get the creative juices flowing again.</i>

06:58.751 --> 07:00.919
<i>I can have George
cable the Ritz for the usual suite.</i>

07:01.003 --> 07:02.337
<i>I'm not talking about Paris.</i>

07:02.380 --> 07:04.506
<i>I'm talking about someplace
completely different.</i>

07:05.299 --> 07:07.175
<i>Like Morocco or Egypt.</i>

07:07.677 --> 07:11.471
<i>Ooh. A boat trip down the Nile.
Sounds so romantic.</i>

07:11.514 --> 07:14.015
<i>I've got just the dress
to wear to the Pyramids.</i>

07:14.058 --> 07:15.100
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

07:15.226 --> 07:16.268
<i>Hey, we could leave next week.</i>

07:16.352 --> 07:17.978
<i>Spend a couple of weeks there.</i>

07:18.020 --> 07:20.188
<i>Maybe stop in Casablanca or Tangiers</i>

07:20.231 --> 07:22.107
<i>as long as we're hopping
around and still be back</i>

07:22.191 --> 07:24.359
<i>- in time for the opening of my new play.
- Ooh.</i>

07:24.402 --> 07:26.653
<i>To Cairo and Morocco and Tangiers.</i>

07:26.696 --> 07:30.365
<i>To all the exotic
and romantic places in the world.</i>

07:32.785 --> 07:36.371
<i>- Hey, there's another room in here.
- Oh, isn't it divine?</i>

07:37.039 --> 07:38.999
<i>Everything's so perfectly preserved.</i>

07:39.041 --> 07:40.876
<i>It's quite lovely.
I just don't want to suddenly feel</i>

07:40.960 --> 07:42.627
<i>- a bandaged hand around my throat.</i>
- (AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

07:42.712 --> 07:43.795
(RITA GASPS)

07:43.880 --> 07:45.172
<i>Hi there. Who are you?</i>

07:45.256 --> 07:47.799
HENRY: <i>Oh, we're sightseeing.
We thought we were alone.</i>

07:47.884 --> 07:49.217
<i>You gave me quite a start.</i>

07:49.302 --> 07:51.511
<i>Oh, I'm awfully sorry. Tom Baxter.</i>

07:51.554 --> 07:52.637
<i>Explorer, adventurer.</i>

07:52.722 --> 07:54.264
<i>I'm doing a little archeological work.</i>

07:54.348 --> 07:56.099
<i>A real life explorer.</i>

07:56.184 --> 07:58.435
<i>I've come in search
of the purple rose of Cairo.</i>

07:58.519 --> 08:01.354
<i>It's an old legend that's
fascinated me for years.</i>

08:01.397 --> 08:04.024
<i>A Pharaoh had a rose
painted purple for his queen</i>

08:04.066 --> 08:05.400
<i>and now the story says,</i>

08:05.485 --> 08:07.819
<i>purple roses grow wild at her tomb.</i>

08:07.904 --> 08:10.155
<i>- How romantic.
- And you?</i>

08:10.239 --> 08:12.240
<i>Ah, we're going back
to New York tomorrow.</i>

08:12.283 --> 08:13.575
<i>It's been a refreshing two weeks.</i>

08:13.659 --> 08:15.577
<i>Say, we should bring him back
to New York to meet the Countess.</i>

08:15.661 --> 08:17.829
<i>- She loves anything in a pith helmet.
- Right.</i>

08:17.914 --> 08:19.080
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

08:19.165 --> 08:20.499
<i>I will say, it's tempting.</i>

08:20.583 --> 08:21.625
<i>Oh, then it's settled.</i>

08:21.709 --> 08:24.419
<i>You can explain to us what we've been
looking at for the last two weeks.</i>

08:24.504 --> 08:26.046
<i>And we can take you nightclubbing.</i>

08:26.088 --> 08:29.424
<i>It's so impulsive, but I'll come.</i>

08:29.509 --> 08:33.511
(CHUCKLING) <i>Why not? I mean,
what's life without a little risk taking?</i>

08:33.596 --> 08:36.932
<i>Who knows? A fortune teller
predicted I'd fall in love in New York.</i>

08:41.854 --> 08:43.813
<i>Table for six, please, Arturo.</i>

08:43.898 --> 08:45.440
<i>Six, sir.</i>

08:48.027 --> 08:49.361
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

09:06.754 --> 09:08.046
(PEOPLE APPLAUDING)

09:08.172 --> 09:10.298
BAND LEADER: <i>Now,
ladies and gentlemen, the Copacabana</i>

09:10.383 --> 09:12.968
<i>is proud to present, Miss Kitty Hayne.</i>

09:17.932 --> 09:23.562
<i>Ours could be a different sort of love affair</i>

09:24.146 --> 09:28.233
<i>Where busybodies couldn't help but stare...</i>

09:28.317 --> 09:29.484
<i>Mmm.</i>

09:29.569 --> 09:33.989
<i>I think our poetic little archeologist
is about to make a discovery.</i>

09:34.824 --> 09:37.158
<i>Well, ain't life swell.</i>

09:37.201 --> 09:38.410
<i>Hey, open the champagne.</i>

09:38.494 --> 09:42.080
<i>I feel like getting plushed to the scuppers.</i>

09:42.164 --> 09:45.584
<i>Let's take it one day at a time</i>

09:45.668 --> 09:50.171
<i>And who cares just how it turns out</i>

09:55.219 --> 09:59.097
CUSTOMER: Ah, check please.
Ah, miss, could I have the check, please?

09:59.515 --> 10:01.683
Come on, the man wants his check.

10:01.767 --> 10:03.518
Oh, sorry.

10:04.729 --> 10:05.895
Sorry.

10:05.980 --> 10:07.689
So what were you thinking about?

10:07.773 --> 10:11.526
Oh, a penthouse, the desert...

10:11.611 --> 10:13.903
- Oh, God.
- Kissing on a dance floor.

10:13.988 --> 10:16.698
So, you did
go to the movies last night after all.

10:16.782 --> 10:17.991
The people were so beautiful.

10:18.034 --> 10:20.160
- They spoke so cleverly...
- Really?

10:20.202 --> 10:21.745
...and they do such romantic things.

10:21.829 --> 10:23.163
- Listen, well, I mean...
- Ah, I'm sorry I missed it.

10:23.205 --> 10:25.081
The one they've got
playing Tom Baxter, he was so cute.

10:25.166 --> 10:26.499
Hey, you want to go
to the movies after work?

10:26.542 --> 10:27.584
Yes, I'd love to.

10:27.668 --> 10:28.668
- I'd love to see it again.
- Let's go then.

10:28.711 --> 10:31.171
Come on, what is this, a social club?
I got a sink full of dirty dishes.

10:31.213 --> 10:33.214
Come on, girls, come on.

10:34.634 --> 10:36.509
CECILIA: Thanks a lot.

10:39.972 --> 10:42.807
<i>Well, I am impressed! I really am.</i>

10:42.892 --> 10:45.393
<i>You have yourself quite a place here.</i>

10:45.811 --> 10:48.146
<i>You know, I still can't get over
the fact that 24 hours ago,</i>

10:48.230 --> 10:49.814
<i>I was in an Egyptian tomb.</i>

10:49.899 --> 10:53.443
<i>I didn't know any of you wonderful people,
and here I am now.</i>

10:53.527 --> 10:57.030
<i>I'm on the verge of a
madcap Manhattan weekend.</i>

10:57.073 --> 10:59.741
<i>I hope you like your martinis very dry.</i>

11:00.242 --> 11:01.618
<i>Oh, no, no, thanks.</i>

11:01.702 --> 11:04.913
<i>I think I'll wait for
that glass of champagne at the Copacabana.</i>

11:08.167 --> 11:09.709
I'm home, Monk.

11:12.088 --> 11:13.171
What are you doing home so early?

11:13.255 --> 11:14.839
I thought I said you can go to the movies.

11:14.924 --> 11:15.965
Yeah, I did.

11:16.050 --> 11:17.759
(WOMAN LAUGHING)

11:20.221 --> 11:21.596
I better go.

11:21.681 --> 11:23.932
(LAUGHING) No, don't, stay. This is Cecilia.

11:24.016 --> 11:27.435
Uh, this is, uh, my friend, Olga.
Olga's an acrobat.

11:27.478 --> 11:28.937
(BOTH LAUGHING)

11:31.273 --> 11:33.692
I am not. I have to go home.

11:33.776 --> 11:35.110
Oh, no, come on, come on,

11:35.152 --> 11:36.820
- I was going to tell your fortune here.
- No, you're drunk.

11:36.904 --> 11:38.655
Uh, what do you mean drunk? I'm not drunk.

11:38.739 --> 11:40.281
Come on, don't worry about her.

11:40.366 --> 11:42.450
She's my ball and chain, or she tries to be.

11:42.535 --> 11:45.036
Olga, Olga, where the hell are you going?

11:45.121 --> 11:47.872
Hey, Olga, come on,
I want to show you a card trick.

11:47.957 --> 11:50.166
- Olga!
- (OLGA LAUGHING)

12:09.145 --> 12:11.146
Is there any more of that meatloaf left?

12:12.690 --> 12:15.817
That stuff you made
yesterday was delicious.

12:16.902 --> 12:19.237
- What's going on?
- I'm moving out.

12:20.489 --> 12:23.158
Now what are you talking about?
What's wrong?

12:24.243 --> 12:26.619
What? Because of before?

12:26.662 --> 12:28.455
Because of Olga? Is that it?

12:28.497 --> 12:30.832
Because that would be funny.
That would be ridiculous

12:30.875 --> 12:32.417
(CHUCKLING) I mean, if it's because of Olga,

12:32.501 --> 12:34.669
you'd be making a bigger fool
out of yourself than you usually are.

12:34.712 --> 12:35.795
Pardon me.

12:36.756 --> 12:38.673
She's Joe Caruso's sister.

12:39.175 --> 12:41.092
And I was just showing her a card trick.

12:41.177 --> 12:43.219
Your undershirt's on backwards.

12:43.304 --> 12:45.054
I put it on that way this morning.

12:45.181 --> 12:47.766
Now listen, Cecilia,
you're making a mistake.

12:48.768 --> 12:50.477
All right, I'm sorry.

12:50.770 --> 12:53.021
I was drinking. You know
how I get when I drink, sweetheart.

12:53.105 --> 12:55.815
- You think it means I don't love you?
- Move.

12:55.858 --> 12:57.400
You can't leave.

12:58.027 --> 12:59.319
I need you.

13:00.362 --> 13:02.781
And you know, I love you.

13:03.491 --> 13:05.825
- Now, look, I made a mistake.
- You don't love me.

13:05.868 --> 13:08.203
- Now, baby, come on.
- (CRYING) You don't. You treat me bad,

13:08.287 --> 13:09.829
and you beat up on me.

13:10.372 --> 13:12.373
Look, I hit you when you get out of line,

13:12.416 --> 13:14.584
and I never just hit you.
I always warn you first,

13:14.668 --> 13:16.461
and then if you don't shape up,
you get whacked.

13:16.545 --> 13:18.588
- I'm leaving.
- Now listen, Cecilia,

13:18.672 --> 13:21.341
I don't know who's
filling your head full of these crazy notions,

13:21.383 --> 13:22.884
but I've had enough.

13:24.386 --> 13:26.971
I want supper. Get my meatloaf.

13:27.056 --> 13:28.389
Uh-uh.

13:28.432 --> 13:31.434
Come on, Cecilia,
you know I can't live without you.

13:31.519 --> 13:33.520
I'm like a little kid when it comes to you.

13:33.562 --> 13:35.772
- That's just tough.
- Look, I'm sorry.

13:35.856 --> 13:38.399
I mean, I'm really sorry. Can't I be sorry?

13:38.442 --> 13:39.859
I drink, I get crazy.

13:39.902 --> 13:41.402
It's not me. It's the whiskey.

13:41.445 --> 13:43.446
I'm going, Monk, I'm going.

13:43.531 --> 13:45.573
Ah, Jesus Christ, I can't reason with you.

13:45.616 --> 13:47.909
All right, go ahead.
Let's see how far you get.

13:47.993 --> 13:49.744
Go on, go on, you won't last.

13:49.787 --> 13:51.621
You see how it is out in the real world.

13:51.705 --> 13:53.289
Go on, you'll come back.

13:53.374 --> 13:56.084
You're just bluff. You're all phony!

13:56.126 --> 13:58.419
You'll be back. It may take a week,

13:58.504 --> 14:01.589
it may take an hour, but you'll be back.

14:18.941 --> 14:20.149
(MEN CHATTERING)

14:22.403 --> 14:25.113
Oh, jeez, look at all those guys.

14:26.615 --> 14:28.658
Come on, honey, we're gonna make a buck.

14:57.146 --> 14:58.563
(MONK SNORING)

15:01.442 --> 15:04.068
I ordered bacon and tomato,
you brought me ham and Swiss.

15:04.653 --> 15:06.362
I'll get it right away, ma'am.

15:06.697 --> 15:08.239
- Cecilia, I want you to meet somebody.
- Who?

15:08.324 --> 15:10.325
Well, remember,
I told you I was going to keep my eyes open

15:10.367 --> 15:11.910
- for eligible men?
- Oh, come on.

15:11.994 --> 15:13.828
- Come on, just keep an open mind.
- Tsk.

15:14.914 --> 15:18.291
This is my sister, Cecilia.
This is Mr. Teddy Ashcroft.

15:18.334 --> 15:19.834
- How do you do?
- Charmed.

15:20.336 --> 15:22.170
Teddy's an exterminator.

15:22.254 --> 15:26.341
Right. Merson's Pest Control.
My specialty are mice and silverfish.

15:27.009 --> 15:28.760
- I'm pleased to meet you.
- Nice to meet you.

15:28.844 --> 15:30.345
CUSTOMER 1: Waitress, please,
my hamburger!

15:30.387 --> 15:31.512
- I'm coming.
- CUSTOMER 2: Can we have a check?

15:31.597 --> 15:33.556
- I'll be right there. Oh!
- (PLATE BREAKING)

15:33.641 --> 15:36.935
That's it.
That's it, Cecilia, you're fired. Get out!

15:37.019 --> 15:39.437
But I'll pay for it. I'll be more careful.

15:39.521 --> 15:42.857
Out. Out.
Take off your apron, go home. You're fired!

15:42.942 --> 15:44.484
If she goes, then I go too.

15:44.526 --> 15:45.860
That's fine with me.

15:45.903 --> 15:47.862
She doesn't mean that. No, you've got kids.

15:47.905 --> 15:49.030
No, she doesn't mean that.

15:49.073 --> 15:51.032
Then tell her to mind her own business.

15:51.075 --> 15:52.367
You're fired.

15:54.161 --> 15:56.079
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

16:05.881 --> 16:08.925
<i>Ah, back from Egypt.
From the Bedouins to Broadway.</i>

16:09.009 --> 16:11.427
<i>Even though I'm not a religious man,
I hereby vow</i>

16:11.512 --> 16:13.346
<i>never to fly over the Atlantic
in bumpy weather,</i>

16:13.389 --> 16:16.224
<i>and never to look at another camel.
Drinks anyone?</i>

16:16.684 --> 16:18.351
RITA: <i>Boy, I can't wait
to get out of these clothes</i>

16:18.394 --> 16:20.520
<i>and hit some of the night spots.</i>

16:20.813 --> 16:22.522
HENRY: <i>Well, children,
let's not waste any time.</i>

16:22.564 --> 16:25.108
<i>The floor show
at the Copacabana starts in 10 minutes,</i>

16:25.192 --> 16:27.402
<i>and we're meeting
the Countess and Larry Wilde.</i>

16:28.112 --> 16:31.197
<i>Well, I am impressed! I really am.</i>

16:31.240 --> 16:33.700
<i>You have yourself quite a place here.</i>

16:34.243 --> 16:36.661
<i>You know, I still can't get over the fact
that 24 hours ago,</i>

16:36.745 --> 16:38.246
<i>I was in an Egyptian tomb.</i>

16:38.288 --> 16:41.874
<i>I didn't know any of you wonderful people,
and here I am now.</i>

16:41.917 --> 16:45.503
<i>I'm on the verge of a
madcap Manhattan weekend.</i>

16:45.587 --> 16:48.589
<i>I hope you like your martinis very dry.</i>

16:48.632 --> 16:49.924
<i>Oh, no, no, thanks.</i>

16:50.009 --> 16:52.552
<i>I think I'll wait for
that glass of champagne at the Copacabana.</i>

16:59.810 --> 17:02.854
<i>Miss Rita, something on your mind?</i>

17:03.272 --> 17:06.232
<i>'Cause you ain't been yourself since you
come back from them pyramids.</i>

17:06.733 --> 17:09.109
<i>No, it's nothing. I'll be okay.</i>

17:09.153 --> 17:13.865
<i>I don't suspect it has anything to do
with that explorer fella, Mr. Tom Baxter.</i>

17:13.949 --> 17:15.782
<i>Now, why would you say that?</i>

17:16.785 --> 17:19.871
<i>The way he speaks, all romantic-like.</i>

17:19.954 --> 17:23.499
<i>Yeah. Come on, Delilah, draw my bath.</i>

17:23.666 --> 17:25.292
<i>Yes, ma'am.</i>

17:25.419 --> 17:29.797
<i>Now, will you be wanting the big bubbles,
or the asses' milk?</i>

17:37.139 --> 17:39.098
<i>Boy, I can't wait to get out of these clothes</i>

17:39.141 --> 17:40.975
<i>and hit some of the night spots.</i>

17:41.060 --> 17:42.935
<i>Well, children, let's not waste any time.</i>

17:43.020 --> 17:45.646
<i>The floor show
at the Copacabana starts in 10 minutes,</i>

17:45.731 --> 17:47.982
<i>and we're meeting
the Countess and Larry Wilde.</i>

17:48.067 --> 17:50.943
<i>Well, I am very impressed. I really am.</i>

17:50.986 --> 17:53.654
<i>You have yourself quite a place here.</i>

17:54.323 --> 17:56.991
<i>You know, I still can't get over the fact
that 24 hours ago,</i>

17:57.034 --> 17:58.451
<i>I was in an Egyptian tomb.</i>

17:58.535 --> 18:00.369
<i>I didn't know any of you wonderful people,</i>

18:02.206 --> 18:07.168
<i>and here I am now. I'm on the verge
of a madcap Manhattan weekend.</i>

18:08.921 --> 18:11.005
<i>My God, you must really love this picture.</i>

18:11.715 --> 18:13.674
- Me?
<i>- You've been here all day,</i>

18:13.759 --> 18:15.218
<i>and I've seen you here twice before.</i>

18:15.969 --> 18:18.387
- You mean me?
<i>- Yes, you, you. You've...</i>

18:18.472 --> 18:21.015
<i>This is the fifth time you're seeing this.</i>

18:21.058 --> 18:23.601
(WHISPERING) <i>Henry, come here, quickly.</i>

18:23.685 --> 18:25.770
<i>- I gotta speak to you.</i>
- (AUDIENCE EXCLAIMING)

18:27.022 --> 18:28.106
(SCREAMS)

18:28.190 --> 18:30.066
HENRY: <i>Listen, old sport,
you're on the wrong side.</i>

18:30.150 --> 18:31.234
<i>Tom, get back here,</i>

18:31.318 --> 18:32.693
<i>- we're in the middle of a story!</i>
- Leave me alone.

18:32.778 --> 18:34.654
I want to have a look around.
You go on without me.

18:34.696 --> 18:36.405
- HENRY: <i>We can't continue with the story!</i>
- Who are you?

18:36.490 --> 18:37.532
(STAMMERING) Cecilia.

18:37.616 --> 18:39.117
I'll go get the manager!

18:39.201 --> 18:41.160
Let's get out of here
and go somewhere where we can talk.

18:41.203 --> 18:42.829
But you're in the movie!

18:42.871 --> 18:44.789
Wrong, Cecilia, I'm free!

18:44.873 --> 18:48.668
After 2,000 performances
of the same monotonous routine, I'm free!

18:48.710 --> 18:50.837
- HENRY: <i>Call Father Donnelly.
- Tom!</i>

18:52.631 --> 18:54.382
I don't understand. What's going on?

18:54.466 --> 18:55.758
- Who are you?
- Who am I?

18:55.843 --> 18:58.553
You've seen the movie five times.
I'm Tom Baxter.

18:58.595 --> 19:01.222
Poet, adventurer, explorer,
of the Chicago Baxters.

19:01.265 --> 19:02.390
Well, yes, I know you're Tom Baxter.

19:02.474 --> 19:04.350
You wind up with Kitty Haynes,
the nightclub singer,

19:04.393 --> 19:05.893
- but still, I don't...
- Not anymore, I don't have to.

19:05.978 --> 19:08.896
- What do you mean?
- Well, I'm out before the wedding. I'm free.

19:08.981 --> 19:10.189
Don't you have to marry her?

19:10.232 --> 19:11.941
Not while I'm here and she's up there.

19:12.025 --> 19:13.693
Don't you want to? She's so beautiful.

19:13.735 --> 19:15.486
She's not for me. She's too bony.

19:15.571 --> 19:17.655
Kitty Haynes, the nightclub singer, is bony?

19:17.739 --> 19:19.323
I need a place to hide!

19:19.408 --> 19:22.076
Look, I'm never going back,
now that I've met you.

19:22.161 --> 19:25.121
A place to hide? A place to hide?

19:25.789 --> 19:27.582
What's happening? What's going on?

19:27.666 --> 19:29.834
<i>Tom's left. He just walked right out.</i>

19:29.918 --> 19:31.794
<i>I don't know how he did it. I can't get out.</i>

19:31.879 --> 19:32.920
<i>This is just disgusting.</i>

19:33.005 --> 19:35.423
<i>I am an heiress
and I don't have to put up with this!</i>

19:35.507 --> 19:36.883
He left the picture?

19:36.925 --> 19:39.010
Oh, my gosh. Well, don't panic.

19:39.094 --> 19:41.179
Just stay up there and keep calm.

19:41.263 --> 19:42.305
<i>Keep calm?</i>

19:42.389 --> 19:43.431
<i>Are you crazy?
What do you mean, "keep calm"?</i>

19:43.473 --> 19:45.141
<i>- Somebody call for a priest?
- Thank God you're here.</i>

19:45.225 --> 19:47.226
<i>- Wait a minute, this is the second reel.
- That's the point.</i>

19:47.269 --> 19:49.145
<i>- I'm not on till later.
- Tom's gone.</i>

19:49.229 --> 19:50.688
Can't you go on? There's an audience.

19:50.772 --> 19:53.065
RITA: <i>How?
Tom was the linchpin of the story.</i>

19:53.108 --> 19:54.567
<i>That's right! Whoever you are, you see, sir,</i>

19:54.610 --> 19:55.651
<i>although this is basically my story,</i>

19:55.736 --> 19:57.653
<i>- Tom moves the exposition along.
- What do you mean, your story?</i>

19:57.738 --> 19:58.738
<i>It's not your story,</i>

19:58.780 --> 20:00.698
<i>it's the story
of a man's quest for self-fulfillment.</i>

20:00.782 --> 20:02.742
<i>- It's the story of a complex, tortured soul.
- Oh, stop that...</i>

20:02.784 --> 20:04.327
<i>It's story of the effect of money
on true romance...</i>

20:04.411 --> 20:05.453
<i>I don't think money comes into it.</i>

20:05.495 --> 20:07.663
<i>...my upbringing, my wealth,
my private schools.</i>

20:07.748 --> 20:09.874
<i>I'm the one who marries royalty.</i>

20:09.958 --> 20:11.250
<i>- I'm the one...
- Nobody cares...</i>

20:11.293 --> 20:12.793
<i>A humble kid...
What do you mean, they don't care?</i>

20:12.878 --> 20:15.171
<i>They wouldn't
sell a ticket if it were your story.</i>

20:15.255 --> 20:17.173
(ALL ARGUING)

20:17.257 --> 20:19.800
- Stop arguing.
- RITA: <i>And do what?</i>

20:19.927 --> 20:21.719
Maybe you should just
turn the projector off.

20:21.803 --> 20:23.763
<i>No! No! Don't turn the projector off!</i>

20:23.847 --> 20:25.681
<i>No! No, it gets black and we disappear.</i>

20:25.766 --> 20:27.642
<i>- Calm down...
- Easy, easy. Easy, easy.</i>

20:27.726 --> 20:29.310
<i>Easy, my son. We're all in this together.</i>

20:29.394 --> 20:32.897
<i>Yes, but you don't
understand what it's like to disappear</i>

20:32.981 --> 20:34.815
<i>and to be nothing, to be annihilated.</i>

20:34.900 --> 20:36.859
<i>So don't turn the projector off.</i>

20:36.944 --> 20:38.694
<i>Miss Rita, your bath is ready.</i>

20:38.820 --> 20:40.655
<i>- Not now, dear.
- Well, what's going on?</i>

20:40.697 --> 20:42.031
<i>- Come in and sit down, Delilah.
- Be quiet, Delilah.</i>

20:42.115 --> 20:43.157
<i>Well, what's he doing here?</i>

20:43.200 --> 20:45.576
<i>- Have a martini.
- He's not supposed to be here till reel six.</i>

20:45.661 --> 20:47.662
<i>- We know that, Delilah.
- What the hell is going on?</i>

20:47.704 --> 20:48.871
<i>Is somebody trying to hustle me?</i>

20:48.956 --> 20:50.081
<i>They're not trying to hustle you.</i>

20:52.668 --> 20:55.044
TOM: Hey, I know what this is,
it's an amusement park!

20:55.128 --> 20:57.922
CECILIA: Yeah, it's usually pretty dead
around here until summer.

20:58.006 --> 21:00.424
I know exactly what an amusement park is,

21:00.509 --> 21:02.718
- and what goes on. I do!
- Well, good.

21:03.512 --> 21:05.137
It's written into my character.

21:05.180 --> 21:06.764
Remember, I invite Kitty to Luna Park,

21:06.848 --> 21:08.391
but she prefers just to stay home and talk?

21:08.475 --> 21:11.018
- Oh, yes.
- So, it's in me!

21:11.103 --> 21:13.521
Oh, too bad nothing's open. I'm starved!

21:13.563 --> 21:14.939
- Oh, you are?
- Well, yeah,

21:15.023 --> 21:17.358
I, uh, left the movie
before the Copacabana scene.

21:17.442 --> 21:19.110
- So that's when I usually eat.
- Oh, wait a minute,

21:19.194 --> 21:21.570
what am I thinking?
Look, here, I've got a whole bag of popcorn.

21:21.655 --> 21:23.489
- You can have that.
- Oh, wow.

21:23.573 --> 21:25.491
Also, I have a Milky Way bar you might...

21:25.575 --> 21:28.160
- No, that's, popcorn is...
- You might want it later.

21:29.538 --> 21:30.579
Boy!

21:30.706 --> 21:32.707
So that's what popcorn tastes like.

21:32.791 --> 21:36.377
I've been watching
people eat it for all those performances.

21:36.420 --> 21:38.671
When they rattle
those bags, though, that's, uh...

21:38.714 --> 21:39.964
- That's not...
- ...kind of annoying.

21:40.048 --> 21:42.300
I still don't understand what's going on.

21:42.384 --> 21:43.884
I wanted to meet you.

21:43.927 --> 21:45.511
Don't tell me you
didn't see me looking at you

21:45.554 --> 21:47.179
just out of the corner of my eye.

21:47.222 --> 21:48.973
When Kitty Haynes
was doing her nightclub number?

21:49.057 --> 21:51.976
Oh, wait a minute,
I did, I remember seeing you kind of...

21:52.102 --> 21:53.936
You were looking
off to the side, somehow, but...

21:54.021 --> 21:56.272
- Sure.
- I never thought it was to me.

21:56.356 --> 21:58.899
Yeah, when we
take the drive to that little country inn?

21:58.942 --> 22:00.901
When I propose to Kitty?
I was looking at you.

22:00.986 --> 22:03.279
Oh, no, Kitty
looked so beautiful in that black dress.

22:03.363 --> 22:05.573
Oh, no, she's nothing compared to you.

22:05.615 --> 22:08.326
What are you talking about? I'm nothing.

22:08.410 --> 22:10.369
Like hell you are. You are fetching.

22:10.412 --> 22:12.455
- Fetching?
- Fetching.

22:12.539 --> 22:15.041
Dad liked to use that word
about Mom back in Chicago.

22:15.083 --> 22:17.418
"Man!" he'd say, "You're rather fetching."

22:17.502 --> 22:18.711
(GIGGLES)

22:19.713 --> 22:20.755
Dad was a card.

22:20.839 --> 22:23.090
I never met him.
He died before the movie begins.

22:23.175 --> 22:26.635
I have to confess.
My eye did always go to you

22:26.720 --> 22:29.930
- up on the screen. Really.
- Really?

22:30.682 --> 22:33.517
Even when I'm around Detective Sims
and Henry Adams, the playboy.

22:33.602 --> 22:36.103
Yes, even though
you're not the main character,

22:36.188 --> 22:37.646
you're the one you look at.

22:38.190 --> 22:39.982
You don't think I'm the main character.

22:40.108 --> 22:42.943
Oh, I didn't mean it that way. No!

22:43.028 --> 22:45.780
I think you were positively essential.

22:45.864 --> 22:48.282
In fact, every time
I saw the movie I kept thinking,

22:48.325 --> 22:50.284
"Tom Baxter's so handsome."

22:50.369 --> 22:51.369
(CHUCKLING)

22:56.291 --> 22:58.125
Shouldn't you be getting back?

22:58.168 --> 23:01.128
I want to live.
I want to be free to make my own choices.

23:01.171 --> 23:03.798
Right now,
the country's not in such great shape.

23:04.633 --> 23:07.385
- What do you mean?
- Well, we're in the middle of a depression.

23:07.469 --> 23:09.136
Everybody's very poor...

23:10.389 --> 23:12.473
I got plenty, look at this!

23:13.642 --> 23:17.353
But, they need you.
The story doesn't work without you.

23:17.854 --> 23:19.855
Cecilia, I'm in love with you.

23:20.816 --> 23:22.233
I'm married...

23:22.776 --> 23:24.151
Happily?

23:25.404 --> 23:27.738
I really should get back home.
I have to cook dinner.

23:27.823 --> 23:29.490
Just slip away from your husband tonight.

23:29.574 --> 23:31.158
Meet me here. I'll wait for you.

23:31.201 --> 23:33.786
I want to learn
about the real world with you.

23:33.829 --> 23:35.246
I can't.

23:35.539 --> 23:36.622
Well, look at it this way.

23:36.665 --> 23:39.166
How many times
is a man so taken with a woman

23:39.209 --> 23:41.210
that he walks off the screen to get her?

23:44.548 --> 23:47.091
<i>Okay, okay, let's not panic. We're all adults.</i>

23:47.175 --> 23:48.843
<i>Bored of sitting around.
I'm a dramatic character.</i>

23:48.885 --> 23:50.010
<i>I need forward motion.</i>

23:50.053 --> 23:51.470
<i>Here comes the Countess and Larry.</i>

23:51.513 --> 23:52.763
<i>Where is everybody?</i>

23:52.848 --> 23:54.473
<i>Weren't we meeting at the Copacabana?</i>

23:54.516 --> 23:56.016
- HENRY: <i>Tom's gone.
- What?</i>

23:56.101 --> 23:57.685
<i>- He left the film.
- What?</i>

23:57.727 --> 23:59.270
<i>The bum walked out on us.</i>

23:59.354 --> 24:01.772
(STAMMERING) <i>But the Copa
is where the two of us meet.</i>

24:01.857 --> 24:03.232
<i>I'm trying to get him to marry me.</i>

24:03.316 --> 24:05.901
<i>Forget it. I'm tired
of marrying you every night anyway.</i>

24:05.986 --> 24:07.236
<i>We never even get to the bedroom.</i>

24:07.362 --> 24:09.864
<i>- Where did Tom go?
- Into the real world.</i>

24:09.948 --> 24:12.032
<i>That two-bit minor character
leaves and we're stuck.</i>

24:12.117 --> 24:13.784
<i>I wonder what it's like out there.</i>

24:13.869 --> 24:16.203
<i>They don't look like
they're having too much fun to me.</i>

24:16.580 --> 24:18.497
Hey, what the hell kind of movie is this?

24:18.540 --> 24:21.208
WOMAN: The paper said it was a romance,
set all over the world!

24:21.293 --> 24:24.211
<i>Look, don't tell us your sad stories.
You think we like this?</i>

24:24.254 --> 24:28.007
Look at this.
They sit around and talk, and no action?

24:28.133 --> 24:30.050
- Nothing happens?
- I want my money back.

24:30.093 --> 24:32.052
- This is outrageous!
<i>- Shh. Why don't you stop yapping?</i>

24:32.095 --> 24:33.387
<i>We've got problems of our own.</i>

24:33.430 --> 24:34.722
You can't talk to my wife like that.

24:34.806 --> 24:35.931
Who do you think you are?

24:36.016 --> 24:38.184
<i>I'm a genuine Countess with a lot of dough,</i>

24:38.226 --> 24:40.311
<i>and if that's your wife, she's a tub of guts.</i>

24:40.395 --> 24:43.189
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

24:45.901 --> 24:47.276
(GLASS SHATTERS)

24:48.069 --> 24:50.237
Hey, what are you so nervous about?

24:50.322 --> 24:52.031
Oh, I'm not.

24:52.866 --> 24:54.241
There's too much pepper in the sauce.

24:54.284 --> 24:56.660
I told you to go easy on the pepper.

24:57.412 --> 24:58.787
Hey, Monk?

24:59.122 --> 25:00.247
Are you, uh...

25:00.290 --> 25:03.792
I guess you and the guys
are probably going out again tonight, huh?

25:03.919 --> 25:06.879
No, I'm not. My back is acting up again.

25:06.922 --> 25:09.298
You gotta give me one
of your special rubdowns. I bought liniment.

25:09.382 --> 25:11.217
- Oh, no.
- What?

25:12.052 --> 25:13.552
Well, I can't.

25:15.388 --> 25:16.639
What do you mean, you can't?

25:16.765 --> 25:18.933
I'm sorry, I didn't mean I can't, I mean,

25:19.017 --> 25:20.601
(STAMMERING) I made some plans, I...

25:20.727 --> 25:22.311
You made plans?

25:22.437 --> 25:25.189
Well, I did. I said I'd...

25:25.273 --> 25:27.608
I'd baby-sit tonight.

25:27.651 --> 25:31.195
I... You know, I ran
into Mrs. Lorenzo and, in the...

25:31.279 --> 25:33.239
I'm saying in the restaurant,
in the street today...

25:33.281 --> 25:35.991
And she has some, you know, I don't know,

25:36.076 --> 25:39.453
I think it was social club meeting or
something she wanted to go to...

25:40.288 --> 25:41.789
Yeah, it won't be too long.

25:41.873 --> 25:44.458
- Yeah, well, I think it's a great idea.
- Yeah?

25:44.584 --> 25:47.336
- Good. Yeah.
- Yeah, because we can use every penny.

25:47.420 --> 25:48.921
All right, so what am I going to do
about my back?

25:48.964 --> 25:51.006
Oh well, don't worry.
You know, I can do some now,

25:51.091 --> 25:52.925
and I'll do some when I come in...

25:52.968 --> 25:55.928
You shouldn't move around too much,
just kind of take it easy.

25:55.971 --> 25:57.972
Well, if you're
gonna go baby-sitting, get paid in cash.

25:58.056 --> 26:00.641
- I will. Okay.
- Don't let her owe you.

26:02.143 --> 26:03.727
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

26:04.813 --> 26:07.231
It's a miracle, a complete miracle!

26:07.315 --> 26:08.857
We want our money back!

26:08.942 --> 26:11.318
I don't pay to watch
those socialites sitting around up there,

26:11.403 --> 26:13.320
and staring back at us,
making nasty remarks.

26:13.363 --> 26:14.738
Is that what they're doing now?

26:14.823 --> 26:16.824
Well, the last time I looked,
the priest had a deck of cards,

26:16.908 --> 26:18.450
and the men were playing pinochle.

26:18.493 --> 26:19.493
How did this first happen?

26:19.578 --> 26:21.954
Well, it's probably all the electrical
storms we had this evening.

26:21.997 --> 26:23.122
The air is charged.

26:23.206 --> 26:24.957
Look, fellas, I depend on the Jewel,

26:25.000 --> 26:28.377
I got personal expenses,
I've got no substitute picture to put in here.

26:28.461 --> 26:30.838
I want my money back! This is a swindle!

26:30.922 --> 26:33.716
There's no story. Mrs. Lupus likes a story.

26:33.800 --> 26:36.635
I still think you should
turn the projector off and shut down.

26:36.678 --> 26:38.345
This could be the work of Reds,
or anarchists.

26:38.430 --> 26:40.306
You can't do that.
If he turns off the projector,

26:40.348 --> 26:44.101
you're liable to strand
this Tom Baxter out in the world someplace.

26:44.185 --> 26:45.686
You want an extra guy running around?

26:45.812 --> 26:48.522
I saw the movie just last week.
This is not what happens!

26:48.607 --> 26:50.357
Where is the Tom Baxter character?

26:50.442 --> 26:52.067
You'll get your money back.

26:52.152 --> 26:54.737
I want what happened
in the movie last week to happen this week,

26:54.821 --> 26:57.031
otherwise what's life all about anyway?

26:57.073 --> 26:58.741
Can't we just go in and take a look?

26:58.825 --> 27:00.409
We don't want to stay long.

27:00.493 --> 27:02.745
If you want to see it,
you have to pay admission.

27:02.829 --> 27:04.496
Okay, keep moving, folks!

27:06.708 --> 27:08.375
<i>Any word about Tom Baxter?</i>

27:08.460 --> 27:09.710
Nothing yet.

27:09.753 --> 27:11.378
<i>So what are you people doing here?</i>

27:11.463 --> 27:14.381
<i>We can't continue
the story till Tom gets back.</i>

27:14.424 --> 27:16.300
Oh, we don't mind observing you all.

27:16.384 --> 27:19.219
Yes, my husband
is a student of the human personality.

27:19.262 --> 27:21.513
<i>Oh, yeah? Well, we're not human.</i>

27:21.556 --> 27:23.891
It doesn't matter to Harold.
He has trouble with humans.

27:23.975 --> 27:25.351
I have trouble?

27:25.393 --> 27:27.394
Where do I have trouble
with the real people?

27:27.437 --> 27:29.647
Oh, I suppose you behave
perfectly with Donald?

27:29.731 --> 27:31.357
He won't speak to my own son-in-law.

27:31.399 --> 27:33.442
I won't speak? The kid is quiet.

27:33.526 --> 27:34.610
He never makes conversation.

27:34.694 --> 27:37.905
- He has to be drawn out.
- I don't like to draw people out.

27:37.947 --> 27:41.033
That's what I said.
He has trouble with live humans.

27:41.534 --> 27:43.869
Yes, yes, R.K.O.

27:44.371 --> 27:47.247
I want to speak to Mr. Raoul Hirsch.

27:48.124 --> 27:50.376
Yes, Mr. Hirsch.

27:50.960 --> 27:54.254
He's the producer of
<i>The Purple Rose Of Cairo.</i> Yes.

27:54.923 --> 27:56.423
No, he's not.

27:56.508 --> 27:58.425
Just tell him I have a theater in New Jersey,

27:58.510 --> 28:00.469
and there's a crisis with his film.

28:01.262 --> 28:03.889
Yes, this is Mr. Hirsch. What's the problem?

28:05.433 --> 28:06.433
What?

28:06.559 --> 28:08.894
They're all just
sitting around up there on the screen.

28:08.937 --> 28:12.439
Rita, the Countess,
Larry Wilde, the playboy.

28:13.358 --> 28:15.109
People are demanding their money back.

28:15.151 --> 28:17.569
The theater is nine-tenths empty.

28:18.154 --> 28:19.697
Come on, take a walk, will you?

28:19.781 --> 28:21.949
Look, he just walked out!

28:22.033 --> 28:24.618
Baxter! The Communist is screaming.

28:24.703 --> 28:26.912
The priest in reel five is in reel two!

28:27.330 --> 28:29.248
How can he come off the screen?
It's impossible.

28:29.290 --> 28:30.708
It's never happened before in history.

28:30.792 --> 28:32.126
Just because a thing never happened before

28:32.168 --> 28:33.794
doesn't mean it can't happen for a first time.

28:33.878 --> 28:35.963
That's all you'll need.
Hundreds of Tom Baxters,

28:36.047 --> 28:37.631
on the loose, running around.

28:37.716 --> 28:38.757
Hundreds?

28:38.800 --> 28:41.552
As your lawyer,
I advise you to get control of it fast.

28:41.636 --> 28:43.637
A character from one of your productions
on the loose?

28:43.722 --> 28:45.222
Who knows what he's capable of?

28:45.306 --> 28:48.016
Robbery, murder. I see lawsuits.

28:48.101 --> 28:51.103
I'd charter a plane right away,
and I'd get down there fast.

28:52.272 --> 28:53.564
Get me Gil Shepherd.

28:54.190 --> 28:55.983
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

28:59.904 --> 29:01.822
Sorry, I'm not too light on my feet.

29:01.865 --> 29:03.949
Oh, no, you're a feather in my arms.

29:03.992 --> 29:05.993
Oh, Monk never took me dancing.

29:06.077 --> 29:08.537
I... Not even when we first met.

29:08.621 --> 29:09.913
Not even if I begged him.

29:09.998 --> 29:12.374
Really? So, it's been bad for you.

29:12.459 --> 29:15.502
Oh, it's been hard for everyone.

29:15.587 --> 29:20.257
You know,
living in a world with no jobs and wars.

29:20.341 --> 29:22.676
You, you probably
never even heard of the Great War.

29:22.761 --> 29:24.303
No, I'm sorry. I missed it.

29:24.345 --> 29:28.724
Yeah, well, people get old and sick

29:28.808 --> 29:31.018
and never find true love.

29:31.352 --> 29:33.729
Boy, you know, where I come from,
people, they don't disappoint.

29:33.813 --> 29:36.774
They're consistent. They're always reliable.

29:37.108 --> 29:39.693
You don't find that kind in real life.

29:40.195 --> 29:41.487
You have.

29:42.197 --> 29:44.114
(LOUD MUSIC PLAYING)

29:46.034 --> 29:47.868
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

29:51.664 --> 29:54.875
Is it true they're talking to you
about the life of Lindbergh?

29:55.043 --> 29:57.669
GIL: It's nearly set,
but don't print it till it's firm.

29:57.712 --> 30:00.047
You were great in <i>The Purple Rose of Cairo.</i>

30:00.131 --> 30:01.757
Thanks, I was, uh...

30:01.883 --> 30:04.885
Did you know I was
singled out by all the East Coast critics?

30:04.928 --> 30:07.930
Mmm-hmm.
The <i>New York Times</i> said that I was...

30:08.056 --> 30:12.267
I had almost too smoldering a quality
to just play comedy.

30:12.352 --> 30:15.562
Would you play Lindbergh
the way you played Tom Baxter?

30:15.647 --> 30:16.980
Would I play... No, of course not.

30:17.065 --> 30:18.732
Tom was kind of a change of pace for me.

30:18.817 --> 30:20.776
He was from my earlier roles.

30:20.860 --> 30:27.241
I played Tom Baxter with a kind of a
poetic, idealistic quality that, uh...

30:27.283 --> 30:31.245
Just... Lindbergh was a loner.
He was just self-reliant.

30:32.413 --> 30:33.664
I'd have to work
it out with my dialogue coach.

30:33.748 --> 30:35.374
He's a genius. He'll...

30:35.416 --> 30:36.917
Gil, can I see you for a minute?
Alone, please?

30:37.001 --> 30:38.335
- Would you excuse me? I'm sorry.
- Sure.

30:38.419 --> 30:40.128
- Right over here.
- What's up?

30:40.213 --> 30:43.340
Tom Baxter's come down off the screen,
and he's running around New Jersey.

30:43.424 --> 30:45.592
- What are you talking about?
- I just spoke to Raoul Hirsch.

30:45.677 --> 30:47.219
Nobody knows how it happened.
But he's done it.

30:47.303 --> 30:49.388
How could he do that?
It's not physically possible.

30:49.430 --> 30:50.931
In New Jersey anything can happen.

30:50.974 --> 30:52.391
But I created the character.

30:52.433 --> 30:53.851
That's my point.

30:54.394 --> 30:56.520
As your agent, I would hate to see
anything happen to your career,

30:56.604 --> 30:57.896
now that it is starting to move.

30:57.939 --> 30:59.189
- What, like, like, like what?
- Who knows?

30:59.274 --> 31:00.732
There's a double of you on the loose.

31:00.775 --> 31:03.402
What's he up to?
Is he robbing banks? Is he raping broads?

31:03.444 --> 31:05.195
- But, is he?
- Who knows?

31:06.030 --> 31:07.364
Look, the last thing we need

31:07.448 --> 31:09.533
- is for you to get a...
- Shh.

31:10.368 --> 31:12.327
The last thing we need
is for you to get a reputation

31:12.412 --> 31:14.496
- as somehow difficult.
- But I'm not, it's not my fault!

31:14.581 --> 31:18.125
Raoul Hirsch already said,
if you can't control your own creation,

31:18.167 --> 31:19.960
- nobody's going to risk a picture on you.
- Oh, my God!

31:20.003 --> 31:22.045
There goes...
I mean, I worked so hard to make him real.

31:22.130 --> 31:23.547
- Yeah, well, maybe you overdid it.
- Jeez!

31:23.631 --> 31:25.007
- I'll sue my dialogue coach, that louse.
- Look,

31:25.091 --> 31:27.217
you've got to fly down there
and check into this, quick.

31:27.302 --> 31:29.636
Right now, it's only one movie house,
but who knows?

31:29.679 --> 31:31.471
I can't, I'm afraid to fly.

31:31.556 --> 31:34.516
Gil, this is the scandal of all time.

31:34.601 --> 31:37.603
You know what happened
to Fatty Arbuckle's career?

31:37.645 --> 31:39.605
- I'll fly. I'll fly.
- Good.

31:40.815 --> 31:42.983
This is how they drink champagne in Cairo.

31:44.569 --> 31:46.361
I never had champagne before.

31:46.487 --> 31:49.323
- I feel... It makes me feel silly.
- It's supposed to.

31:49.449 --> 31:50.657
(CHUCKLING) Yeah.

31:50.783 --> 31:51.950
The check, as you requested, sir.

31:51.993 --> 31:53.201
Ah.

31:53.286 --> 31:55.287
Ah! It's so much!

31:55.330 --> 31:57.122
- Oh...
- I hope found it to your liking, sir.

31:57.832 --> 31:59.499
- It was superb.
- Oh, it was. It was wonderful.

31:59.584 --> 32:01.710
My compliments to the chef.

32:01.794 --> 32:04.463
And, uh, keep 20% for yourself.

32:04.547 --> 32:07.257
No, make that 30%.

32:07.342 --> 32:08.967
Yes, quite amusing.

32:09.844 --> 32:12.012
- What is?
- The fake money.

32:12.764 --> 32:14.348
Fake money?

32:14.432 --> 32:17.059
Is it, uh, play money, sir, or stage money?

32:19.062 --> 32:22.022
Keep 30% for yourself,
and stop looking so serious.

32:23.316 --> 32:24.858
I'll get the Maitre D'.

32:25.860 --> 32:27.986
Tom, that's not real money.

32:28.529 --> 32:31.490
Well, what do you mean it's not real money?

32:32.200 --> 32:33.367
Oh, my God.

32:34.410 --> 32:36.328
Uh, do you have any money?

32:36.371 --> 32:38.372
No. What are we going to do?

32:39.082 --> 32:40.624
We're going to have to make a run for it.

32:40.708 --> 32:43.877
No, I can't run.
My ankles are bad from waitressing.

32:44.212 --> 32:46.046
Just get up. Follow me.

33:00.228 --> 33:02.104
TOM: Quick, get in the car.

33:05.191 --> 33:06.858
Tom, this is not our car!

33:06.901 --> 33:08.527
We don't have a car. We came by foot.

33:08.569 --> 33:10.445
- It doesn't go.
- Well, of course, it doesn't go.

33:10.530 --> 33:11.655
There's no key.

33:11.739 --> 33:13.031
I just, hey, I don't understand.

33:13.074 --> 33:14.616
- This is how I always go in the movie.
- Oh, Tom,

33:14.701 --> 33:16.994
this is real life.
They don't start without a key!

33:17.078 --> 33:18.829
- They don't? Let's go.
- No!

33:18.913 --> 33:20.580
- Hey, you two, get back here!
- They're leaving.

33:20.623 --> 33:21.832
You can't run out on these checks.

33:21.916 --> 33:23.083
They're a couple of deadbeats.

33:23.167 --> 33:24.668
Get back here, right now!

33:28.089 --> 33:29.965
TOM: I'm sorry about the money.
I had no idea.

33:30.049 --> 33:31.842
CECILIA: Oh, that's okay.

33:31.926 --> 33:35.137
It's not going to be so easy
to get along without it in this world.

33:35.221 --> 33:37.347
TOM: Oh, I guess I have to get a job.

33:37.432 --> 33:38.974
But that's not going to be so easy, either.

33:39.058 --> 33:40.934
Right now, the whole country's out of work.

33:41.019 --> 33:42.936
Well, then we'll live on love.

33:42.979 --> 33:45.105
We'll have to make some concessions,
but so what?

33:45.189 --> 33:47.649
- We'll have each other.
- That's movie talk.

33:47.734 --> 33:50.235
You look so beautiful in this light.

33:50.278 --> 33:51.945
But you're not real.

34:01.622 --> 34:03.874
Was that real enough for you?

34:05.168 --> 34:08.795
You kiss perfectly.
It's what I dreamed kissing would be like.

34:08.880 --> 34:10.880
Come away with me to Cairo.

34:10.965 --> 34:11.965
Cairo?

34:12.007 --> 34:15.677
We'll live in the desert.
It will... Oh, the blue-gold light of sunset

34:15.762 --> 34:17.596
- falling over your hair and the...
- Look, I'm sorry.

34:17.638 --> 34:20.806
I'm a little tipsy. I... From the...

34:30.318 --> 34:32.652
- Where's the fade out?
- What?

34:33.237 --> 34:36.322
Always when the kissing gets hot and
heavy, just before the love-making,

34:36.364 --> 34:37.866
there's a fade out.

34:37.949 --> 34:39.868
Oh, then what?

34:39.952 --> 34:43.538
Then, then we're making love
in some private, perfect place.

34:43.623 --> 34:47.333
Oh, that's not how it happens here.

34:48.252 --> 34:50.337
- What, there's no fade out?
- No...

34:50.838 --> 34:54.424
But when you kissed me,
I felt like my heart faded out,

34:54.509 --> 34:59.262
and I closed my eyes
and I was in some, some private place.

35:00.515 --> 35:01.807
How fascinating.

35:01.849 --> 35:04.101
You make love without fading out?

35:04.185 --> 35:05.769
- (BOTH CHUCKLING)
- Yes.

35:06.729 --> 35:08.855
Well, I can't wait to see this.

35:09.982 --> 35:12.651
Listen, I can't...

35:12.693 --> 35:14.861
I'm not that kind of girl.

35:14.946 --> 35:16.613
I'm married.

35:18.116 --> 35:20.367
Cecilia,

35:20.451 --> 35:23.411
it's clear how miserable
you are with your husband,

35:25.248 --> 35:28.708
and if he hits you again, you tell me.

35:29.085 --> 35:31.211
I'd be forced to knock his teeth out.

35:31.254 --> 35:33.338
I don't think that would be such a good idea.

35:33.381 --> 35:34.798
He's big.

35:34.882 --> 35:36.842
Well, I'm sorry.
It's written into my character to do it,

35:36.884 --> 35:38.051
so I do it.

35:39.053 --> 35:42.514
Listen, I think I better go home now.

35:42.557 --> 35:44.057
- It's late.
- Okay.

35:44.142 --> 35:45.517
It's been a whirlwind of a day.

35:45.560 --> 35:46.726
- Don't you think?
- Yeah.

35:46.769 --> 35:48.228
What are you gonna do?

35:48.938 --> 35:51.273
Um, I'll just... I'll sleep here at the carousel.

35:51.357 --> 35:54.568
And walk around, drink in the night air.

35:54.652 --> 35:58.113
Enjoy my freedom, and dream of you.

36:08.040 --> 36:09.499
You got in late last night.

36:09.584 --> 36:11.710
Oh, yeah, you were out like a light.

36:11.752 --> 36:13.753
I took a hot bath to relax me.

36:13.796 --> 36:15.589
You want to get me a cup of coffee?

36:15.631 --> 36:17.257
Oh, yeah, sure.

36:17.300 --> 36:20.093
There was some big
deal going on over at the movie house.

36:20.136 --> 36:21.928
A big crowd when I went to buy cigarettes.

36:21.971 --> 36:24.097
- Yeah?
- Yeah, I couldn't get the story straight.

36:24.182 --> 36:26.933
There's some guy
who ran out the side exit with a customer.

36:26.976 --> 36:29.811
- Who?
- Oh, a woman, a guy, uh, an actor.

36:29.896 --> 36:31.563
I don't know what
the hell the cop was talking about.

36:31.606 --> 36:32.606
He didn't know.

36:32.690 --> 36:35.400
Well, they don't know who the woman was?

36:35.443 --> 36:37.903
Some woman dragged out in the dark.

36:37.945 --> 36:40.030
They got those real geronimos
at the movie houses.

36:40.114 --> 36:42.282
See, that's why
I don't like you staying out so late at night.

36:42.366 --> 36:43.909
(STAMMERING) I know. I couldn't help it.

36:43.951 --> 36:46.161
The Lorenzos didn't get back till late.

36:46.245 --> 36:47.287
I couldn't leave.

36:47.371 --> 36:49.623
- Well, I hope you got paid overtime.
- Oh, sure.

36:49.707 --> 36:51.958
Oh, good, good. Let's have it.

36:52.043 --> 36:54.628
(STUTTERING) They, uh...
They didn't have any cash.

36:54.712 --> 36:56.796
I'll have to come back for it later today.

36:56.881 --> 36:59.257
Cecilia, I told you
to get paid, uh, in cash, didn't I?

36:59.300 --> 37:02.636
Well, I know, but all they had was big bills,

37:02.762 --> 37:04.137
and, um, you know, I was getting late,

37:04.222 --> 37:05.222
- so I thought I better leave.
- Yeah, well,

37:05.306 --> 37:07.057
- they're going to fork it over today, right?
- Oh, they will.

37:07.141 --> 37:08.141
Yeah, yeah, sure.

37:08.184 --> 37:12.270
Leave something to you,
you can bet you're going to get fouled up.

37:18.361 --> 37:19.986
You have no idea where he went?

37:20.279 --> 37:22.489
<i>Mr. Hirsch, this is awful for us.</i>

37:22.615 --> 37:23.907
<i>- Really difficult.</i>
- Think of me,

37:23.991 --> 37:25.742
my reputation, my career!

37:25.826 --> 37:27.786
First thing we've gotta do,
is we gotta keep it contained.

37:27.828 --> 37:28.995
- Yeah.
- The word's out already.

37:29.080 --> 37:30.163
We gotta keep the crisis local.

37:30.206 --> 37:32.624
I know the two reporters in town.
They're old friends.

37:32.667 --> 37:33.667
- Maybe I could talk to them.
- Fine,

37:33.751 --> 37:36.002
a couple of bucks
spread around town will buy us some time.

37:36.045 --> 37:37.212
Don't worry about a thing...

37:37.296 --> 37:39.464
<i>I mean, we're all so lost.</i>

37:39.507 --> 37:40.548
HIRSCH: I know it's rough.

37:40.633 --> 37:42.384
I just want the whole cast to know

37:42.468 --> 37:45.262
how much I appreciate
your staying up there on the screen.

37:45.346 --> 37:48.014
I hope you're not
going to hold this against me, R.H.

37:48.057 --> 37:50.475
You created the part of Tom Baxter, Gil.

37:50.518 --> 37:51.768
The facts are undeniable.

37:51.852 --> 37:54.437
<i>I want to go too.
I want to be free! I want out!</i>

37:54.522 --> 37:56.648
I'm warning you, that's Communist talk!

37:56.691 --> 37:58.316
We're gonna
have to pull the film out of the theater

37:58.359 --> 38:00.277
and you're going
to have to make good my receipts.

38:00.361 --> 38:02.028
<i>You mean, you're thinking of pulling the film</i>

38:02.071 --> 38:03.446
<i>because a minor character is missing?</i>

38:03.531 --> 38:05.448
A minor character? Would you listen to her?

38:05.533 --> 38:07.826
You know, he may not have the most lines,

38:07.868 --> 38:09.411
but the plot turns on Baxter.

38:09.495 --> 38:12.289
I deliberately played him
with a cheerful bravado.

38:12.373 --> 38:13.832
<i>Who cares how you played him?</i>

38:13.874 --> 38:14.916
<i>- He's minor.
- That's right.</i>

38:15.001 --> 38:16.376
I would just like to get my hands on him.

38:16.419 --> 38:18.044
Right when my career was taking off.

38:18.129 --> 38:20.046
<i>He could be raping
that woman he abducted.</i>

38:20.089 --> 38:22.966
And he's got my fingerprints,
my exact prints!

38:23.050 --> 38:25.719
<i>You know what
they get for rape in a small town,</i>

38:25.761 --> 38:27.846
<i>especially by a man in a pith helmet?</i>

38:27.888 --> 38:30.682
If this is the start of a new trend,
our industry's as good as dead.

38:30.725 --> 38:34.728
The real ones want their lives fiction,
and the fictional ones want their lives real.

38:34.770 --> 38:36.396
Does anybody know who that woman was?

38:36.480 --> 38:38.565
No. It was all so crazy, nobody noticed.

38:39.317 --> 38:42.110
Just two doughnuts
and a container of coffee to go, please.

38:42.194 --> 38:44.237
GIL: Right now, it's chaos.

38:45.072 --> 38:47.532
Well, how can rumors
be circulating at the Brown Derby?

38:47.575 --> 38:50.035
It just happened! Well, squash it, Herbie,

38:50.077 --> 38:51.786
I got a career on the line.

38:52.705 --> 38:55.540
Look, I'll call you the minute I hear.

38:57.793 --> 38:59.044
Oh, excuse me.

38:59.170 --> 39:00.420
(GASPING) What are you doing here?

39:00.463 --> 39:03.006
I'm... I'm sorry. I don't have a pencil,
or I'd give you an autograph.

39:03.090 --> 39:05.091
Where did you get those clothes?

39:05.134 --> 39:07.844
- Pardon me?
- Your clothes, where did you get them?

39:07.928 --> 39:10.263
Uh, a little store on Sunset and Vine.

39:10.348 --> 39:11.890
What are you talking about?

39:11.932 --> 39:13.683
What are you talking about?

39:13.768 --> 39:14.934
Excuse me.

39:15.519 --> 39:17.937
I just bought you these. Two doughnuts.

39:18.064 --> 39:20.774
- For me? Well, thank you very much.
- Yeah. A container of coffee.

39:20.816 --> 39:21.941
I hope you enjoy my next movie.

39:22.026 --> 39:25.070
But, do you, I thought
you were going to stay hidden at the park.

39:25.112 --> 39:26.446
What park?

39:26.530 --> 39:27.864
Tom, what's the matter with you?

39:27.948 --> 39:31.117
- You're acting so peculiar.
- Tom? No, no. I'm...

39:31.535 --> 39:33.995
Wait a minute! Come here.

39:34.872 --> 39:36.414
What's come over you?

39:36.457 --> 39:38.291
I'm not Tom. I'm Gil Shepherd.

39:38.334 --> 39:40.001
- I play Tom.
- What?

39:40.086 --> 39:41.920
- How do you know Tom?
- You're Gil...

39:42.046 --> 39:44.255
- Oh, my God. I don't believe it.
- Yeah.

39:44.298 --> 39:46.966
You're Gil... I've seen you in lots of movies.

39:47.051 --> 39:50.136
- Look, where's Tom?
- Oh! <i>Broadway Bachelors,</i> right? Right?

39:50.221 --> 39:52.722
- Yeah, yeah, well, you know...
<i>- Honeymoon in Haiti?</i>

39:52.807 --> 39:54.516
- Done about six.
- You were a scream.

39:54.600 --> 39:56.267
- Well, thank you.
- (EXCLAIMING)

39:56.310 --> 39:57.894
Thank you very much. That's...

39:57.978 --> 40:00.146
I try to do one a year,
you know, just to keep...

40:00.189 --> 40:02.649
Where's Tom?

40:02.733 --> 40:03.942
Why?

40:03.984 --> 40:06.194
Well, he's my character. I created him.

40:06.278 --> 40:08.405
Well, didn't the man
who wrote the movie do that?

40:08.489 --> 40:10.657
Yes, technically.

40:10.699 --> 40:12.784
But I made him live. I fleshed him out.

40:12.827 --> 40:16.579
But you did...
You did a wonderful job. He's adorable.

40:16.664 --> 40:18.790
(CHUCKLING) Thank you very much.

40:19.750 --> 40:21.167
(SIGHING) What's your name?

40:21.293 --> 40:22.710
Cecilia.

40:22.795 --> 40:24.087
Cecilia.

40:24.171 --> 40:25.338
(GASPING)

40:25.506 --> 40:26.673
Where is he?

40:26.757 --> 40:29.592
- Why?
- Has he done anything wrong?

40:29.677 --> 40:30.760
Wrong, like what?

40:30.845 --> 40:33.972
Has he stolen anything
or attacked any females? You?

40:34.014 --> 40:37.517
No, gosh, no, no, he's as sweet as can be.

40:37.601 --> 40:39.811
Well, I played him sweet.
I was well reviewed.

40:39.854 --> 40:41.354
Well, it comes across.

40:41.397 --> 40:43.940
Good. Look, I gotta speak to him.

40:44.358 --> 40:45.650
You're not upset with him?

40:45.693 --> 40:47.152
Well, a little, yes,

40:47.194 --> 40:49.612
but I know if I spoke to him,
we could straighten everything out.

40:49.697 --> 40:51.322
Oh, I don't know.

40:51.365 --> 40:53.366
Please, I have a right.

40:53.868 --> 40:55.743
Well, it has to be secret.

40:55.828 --> 40:58.204
He doesn't want to have
to go back into the movie.

40:58.289 --> 41:01.082
- He doesn't?
- No, he loves being free.

41:01.167 --> 41:03.918
- He's having the time of his life.
- Oh, my God.

41:04.003 --> 41:06.880
Would you take me to him? Trust me.

41:08.090 --> 41:09.174
Please.

41:11.635 --> 41:13.136
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

41:20.227 --> 41:25.023
Monk, somebody saw your wife last night
at the Dine and Dance Joint.

41:25.065 --> 41:27.150
Oh, sure, she's there every night
with the Rockefellers.

41:27.234 --> 41:29.319
Uh, she was with this crazy-looking guy

41:29.403 --> 41:31.905
- wearing an explorer's hat and britches.
- Come on.

41:32.031 --> 41:33.364
Britches?

41:33.407 --> 41:36.242
You know, you're nuts.
She was baby-sitting.

41:36.911 --> 41:39.078
Right. I guess you know it all.

41:43.584 --> 41:45.251
All right, who's next?

41:53.469 --> 41:57.138
(SOFTLY) Tom? Tom?

41:59.058 --> 42:02.936
- Cecilia, I dreamed of us in Cairo.
- Tom. Tom...

42:03.604 --> 42:05.897
- I brought Gil Shepherd.
- Gil... Gil Shepherd.

42:05.940 --> 42:08.107
- I play you in the movie.
- You do?

42:08.192 --> 42:10.235
How dare you run away!

42:10.277 --> 42:11.736
This is disconcerting.

42:11.779 --> 42:14.614
Oh, I'll show you
the meaning of disconcerting.

42:14.657 --> 42:15.949
I'm trying to build a career!

42:16.033 --> 42:17.992
Yeah, well,
I don't want to be in the film anymore.

42:18.077 --> 42:19.327
I'm in love with Cecilia.

42:19.411 --> 42:21.496
Mr. Shepherd, you said you weren't angry.

42:21.580 --> 42:23.373
You can't do this to me. It's my best role.

42:23.457 --> 42:25.083
I've been critically acclaimed for this.
It's my very...

42:25.125 --> 42:26.709
I'd say it's because of the way I do it.

42:26.794 --> 42:29.754
No, no, no, because of the way I do it.
I'm doing it, not you.

42:29.797 --> 42:32.465
It's me, not him. I mean, isn't that obvious?

42:32.508 --> 42:34.300
Well, then, how do you
explain that here I am?

42:34.426 --> 42:36.010
Well, because
I took you from the printed page,

42:36.095 --> 42:37.887
and I made you live.
I fleshed you out, just like...

42:37.972 --> 42:40.890
- So, I'm living.
- Yes, but for the screen only, please.

42:40.975 --> 42:42.642
- And as soon...
- I want my freedom.

42:42.726 --> 42:44.644
I don't want another one of me
running around the world.

42:44.687 --> 42:46.312
I mean, I can
just imagine what he's been up...

42:46.355 --> 42:48.106
Why? Are you afraid I'll embarrass you?

42:48.148 --> 42:49.482
Yes. Frankly, I am afraid...

42:49.525 --> 42:50.692
But, you created me.

42:50.776 --> 42:52.610
All right, look, be reasonable here.

42:52.653 --> 42:54.737
I'm starting to build a career.

42:54.822 --> 42:56.614
Is life up on the screen so terrible that you...

42:56.657 --> 42:59.617
I want to be with Cecilia.
I'm in love with her.

43:00.786 --> 43:01.953
Will you tell him to go back?

43:01.996 --> 43:03.746
Tell him that you don't love him.

43:03.831 --> 43:04.914
Tell him you can't love him.

43:04.999 --> 43:06.082
He's fictional!

43:06.166 --> 43:08.334
You want to waste your time
with a fictional character?

43:08.419 --> 43:10.670
I mean, you're a sweet girl.
You deserve an actual human.

43:10.713 --> 43:12.422
But Tom's perfect.

43:12.506 --> 43:13.798
Yeah, but he's not real.

43:13.841 --> 43:16.718
What good is perfect if the man's not real?

43:16.802 --> 43:18.428
I can learn to be real.

43:18.512 --> 43:20.305
It's easy. You know, there's nothing to it.

43:20.347 --> 43:22.098
Being real comes very naturally to me.

43:22.182 --> 43:24.434
Can't learn to be real.
It's like learning to be a midget.

43:24.518 --> 43:25.852
It's not a thing you can learn.

43:25.894 --> 43:27.937
Some of us are real, some are not.

43:28.022 --> 43:30.315
I say I can do it.

43:30.357 --> 43:31.941
I'm not going to stay here
and argue with you.

43:32.026 --> 43:33.192
I'm gonna go back to town.

43:33.277 --> 43:36.362
I'm going to call my attorney,
the Actors' Union.

43:36.864 --> 43:38.615
I won't take this lying down.

43:38.699 --> 43:42.577
Nor will Raoul Hirsch, nor the police,

43:42.661 --> 43:44.662
nor the FBI.

43:46.290 --> 43:48.166
Yes, yes, we found him.

43:48.834 --> 43:50.209
Gil Shepherd found him,

43:50.294 --> 43:52.587
but he refuses to get back on the screen.

43:52.671 --> 43:54.672
R.H. is very upset.

43:54.715 --> 43:58.176
No, no, we can't force him. It's not a crime.

43:58.218 --> 44:00.053
We need a plan.

44:00.095 --> 44:01.888
Yeah, the press is on our side.

44:01.972 --> 44:04.599
It took a few bucks,
but they're going to keep it quiet for now.

44:04.683 --> 44:07.352
Uh, what? Really?

44:09.104 --> 44:11.773
The Tom Baxter character
in a movie house in Chicago

44:11.857 --> 44:13.900
has been forgetting his lines.

44:13.942 --> 44:16.361
I just got a call from the manager.

44:16.403 --> 44:18.946
If anybody wants me,
I'll be in the bathroom.

44:19.031 --> 44:20.907
On the floor, weeping.

44:23.911 --> 44:26.663
I mean, you do...
Aren't you at all even worried?

44:26.747 --> 44:29.248
Well, what about
Raoul Hirsch and what, the FBI?

44:29.333 --> 44:31.417
No, Cecilia,
if I can be with you, I'm never going back.

44:31.502 --> 44:33.002
- But I, you know...
- No more buts.

44:33.087 --> 44:35.213
I said I was going
to learn about the real world with you.

44:35.255 --> 44:36.506
Show me.

44:40.594 --> 44:42.887
(INAUDIBLE)

45:19.842 --> 45:23.720
TOM: It's beautiful.
But I'm not sure exactly what it is.

45:23.804 --> 45:28.099
Oh, this is a church.
You do believe in God, don't you?

45:28.142 --> 45:29.976
Meaning?

45:30.060 --> 45:35.732
Mmm, the reason for everything,
the, the world, the universe...

45:35.816 --> 45:36.816
Oh, I think I know what you mean.

45:36.900 --> 45:39.152
The two men who wrote, uh,
<i>The Purple Rose of Cairo.</i>

45:39.236 --> 45:42.155
Irving Sachs and R.H. Levine,
the writers who collaborate on films.

45:42.239 --> 45:45.491
No, no, I'm talking
about something much bigger than that.

45:45.534 --> 45:49.203
No, think for a minute.
A reason for everything.

45:49.288 --> 45:52.498
Otherwise, it'd be
like a movie with no point,

45:52.583 --> 45:53.833
and no happy ending.

45:53.876 --> 45:55.501
So there you are!

45:56.128 --> 45:57.628
I'm looking for you.

45:57.671 --> 45:59.714
Monk, I, um...

46:01.091 --> 46:04.761
This is my husband. This is Tom Baxter.

46:04.845 --> 46:07.972
Adventurer, explorer, the Chicago Baxters.
I'm charmed to meet you.

46:08.015 --> 46:10.141
So you wear the britches.

46:10.184 --> 46:11.768
CECILIA: What did you want
to talk to me about?

46:11.852 --> 46:14.604
I heard you were out on the town last night.

46:14.688 --> 46:18.024
Yeah, I'm sorry.
I admit I didn't tell the truth about that,

46:18.066 --> 46:21.027
but things have
been so strange the last 24 hours...

46:21.069 --> 46:22.403
You know what I told you I'd do to you

46:22.488 --> 46:23.780
- if you ever lied to me?
- Monk, don't hit me.

46:23.864 --> 46:25.948
Obviously, your marriage
has come to an impasse, sir.

46:26.033 --> 46:27.533
And you keep out of this.

46:27.618 --> 46:29.827
- Monk, let's just talk.
- No, you're coming home with me!

46:29.870 --> 46:31.412
- Can't we talk?
- Perhaps you don't understand, sir,

46:31.497 --> 46:32.538
but I'm in love with your wife.

46:32.623 --> 46:34.123
Close your yap, jackass.

46:34.208 --> 46:35.208
Now let's go. You're in for a lesson...

46:35.292 --> 46:37.210
You're failing to understand, sir.

46:37.294 --> 46:38.377
She's not coming with you.

46:38.420 --> 46:40.630
- Oh, she's not, huh?
- No, you take your hands off.

46:40.714 --> 46:42.715
No man will hit the woman I love,
nor any woman.

46:42.800 --> 46:46.219
- Beat it! Beat it. I'm gonna take you apart!
- Stop it!

46:46.261 --> 46:48.012
- He's got a terrible temper.
- And you, go home.

46:48.055 --> 46:51.307
Sorry, it's written into my character.
Courage.

46:51.391 --> 46:52.600
Stop it!

47:00.692 --> 47:03.194
- Come on.
- Stop it! What are you doing?

47:15.082 --> 47:16.415
Time for the old one-two.

47:16.458 --> 47:18.000
(GRUNTING)

47:19.795 --> 47:21.587
Hope he's had enough.

47:22.005 --> 47:24.298
Sorry, pal. Sorry about the rough stuff.

47:24.383 --> 47:25.508
- You all right?
- Yeah.

47:25.592 --> 47:26.926
Let me give you a hand. There's a...

47:26.969 --> 47:30.429
(GRUNTING) God, it's not fair. Oh!

47:34.476 --> 47:36.853
Tom! What are you doing?

47:37.396 --> 47:39.564
- You're coming home with me now.
- No, I'm not!

47:39.606 --> 47:40.606
What'd you say?

47:40.691 --> 47:42.650
No, I'm going to stay
and see that Tom's okay.

47:42.734 --> 47:43.943
- I...
- You're a bully, Monk.

47:43.986 --> 47:44.986
I gave you an order.

47:45.070 --> 47:46.863
I don't care. I'm tired of taking your orders.

47:46.947 --> 47:48.072
You could've killed him.

47:48.115 --> 47:50.658
All right. I'm sorry. I didn't mean it.

47:50.742 --> 47:51.742
- I hit hard.
- You can't just...

47:51.785 --> 47:53.995
You can't just
go through life beating people up.

47:54.079 --> 47:56.080
Look, I'm telling you one more time.
Are you coming with me?

47:56.123 --> 47:57.540
No, I'm not.

47:58.500 --> 48:00.376
I'm telling you one more time. You coming?

48:00.460 --> 48:02.795
- No! No, I'm not!
- Come on!

48:04.798 --> 48:07.633
The hell with it. I need a beer anyway.

48:07.718 --> 48:09.468
I'll see you later.

48:12.139 --> 48:14.056
Oh, are you okay?

48:14.141 --> 48:16.475
Oh, oh, yeah. I'm fine.

48:16.560 --> 48:17.727
You're not even marked.

48:17.811 --> 48:19.645
Your hair is in place.

48:19.730 --> 48:21.480
No, no. I don't get hurt or bleed.

48:21.523 --> 48:22.607
Hair doesn't muss.

48:22.649 --> 48:24.817
It's one of the advantages
of being imaginary.

48:24.860 --> 48:26.569
- (CHUCKLES)
- You were very brave.

48:26.653 --> 48:30.406
Yeah, well, I had him, too,
till he started fighting dirty.

48:30.490 --> 48:33.534
That's why you'll never
survive off the screen.

48:33.619 --> 48:36.996
You were pretty brave, too.
You stood right up to him.

48:37.039 --> 48:38.664
You inspired me.

48:51.845 --> 48:53.596
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

48:54.806 --> 48:56.015
CECILIA: Mr. Shepherd.

48:56.099 --> 48:59.185
Oh, Cecilia, look, I got to speak to you.

48:59.227 --> 49:01.979
Oh, listen, I've had a crazy morning.

49:02.022 --> 49:04.273
- I'm still shaking.
- Look, I don't know what to do, all right?

49:04.358 --> 49:05.775
I've struggled my whole life.

49:05.859 --> 49:08.069
And now I'm
finally beginning to break through

49:08.153 --> 49:09.946
and my whole career's
going right down the drain.

49:10.030 --> 49:12.490
You don't have to worry about that.

49:12.532 --> 49:15.368
You'll always be a great movie star.

49:15.452 --> 49:20.122
Oh, well, that's very nice of you to say,
but technically, I'm not really a star yet.

49:20.207 --> 49:24.251
(CHUCKLING) Cecilia, you know, I mean,
I try to carry myself like one.

49:24.336 --> 49:27.338
You know, I do the best I can
as far as that, but star?

49:27.381 --> 49:30.091
Phew! That's a big word, isn't it? Star?

49:30.717 --> 49:32.969
Yeah, uh, no, no.

49:33.053 --> 49:34.428
No, star, no, no.

49:34.513 --> 49:39.100
And you're not just a pretty face,
you're also a peach of an actor.

49:39.184 --> 49:41.686
Really, I've seen you. I've seen you a lot.

49:41.728 --> 49:43.562
You've got something.

49:44.398 --> 49:45.564
- Is that your opinion?
- Sure.

49:45.649 --> 49:47.400
And I see all the movies.

49:47.484 --> 49:51.153
You've got, oh, how can I describe it?

49:53.073 --> 49:55.241
You've got a magical glow.

49:55.325 --> 49:57.743
(CHUCKLING) Oh, boy. Oh, oh.

49:57.828 --> 50:01.414
To hear that from a real person,
that is just...

50:01.456 --> 50:03.165
(EXHALING) It's not
one of those movie colony bimbos,

50:03.250 --> 50:06.711
you know, with the fancy dresses,
filling you full of hot air.

50:06.753 --> 50:08.629
Would you get over here
and sit down, please?

50:08.714 --> 50:10.881
Oh, you know, you can take it from me.

50:10.924 --> 50:12.425
You're not just a flash in the pan.

50:12.509 --> 50:15.928
No, you know, it'd be very easy
for me to trade on my looks.

50:16.013 --> 50:17.054
- Just, like that.
- Oh, sure.

50:17.097 --> 50:18.764
But I have some serious acting ambitions.

50:18.849 --> 50:20.933
You should. You should.

50:21.018 --> 50:24.270
You, you know...
I think you're great in all the funny movies.

50:24.354 --> 50:25.604
Thank you.

50:25.689 --> 50:26.814
Really, I was thinking you should,

50:26.898 --> 50:29.316
you should
play some of the more heroic parts.

50:29.401 --> 50:30.401
I want...

50:30.444 --> 50:32.153
- I tell my agent that a hundred times!
- Yeah?

50:32.237 --> 50:35.114
Well, you know, well, you could play...

50:35.157 --> 50:37.783
You could play,
like, Daniel Boone, or someone...

50:37.868 --> 50:39.535
- Lindbergh! Oh...
- Oh!

50:39.619 --> 50:41.412
- You'd be wonderful as Lindbergh.
- My God!

50:41.455 --> 50:43.456
- You are a mind reader.
- We had the same thought?

50:43.498 --> 50:46.208
- Really?
- I am on the verge of signing for that part.

50:46.293 --> 50:48.627
- No! Really?
- I'm, I am! I can taste it.

50:48.670 --> 50:50.504
Oh, you'll be wonderful.

50:50.589 --> 50:53.132
- Well, thank you.
- Oh, there's something inside you that...

50:53.175 --> 50:56.510
You have that
same kind of lone heroic quality.

50:56.595 --> 50:59.138
You're exactly right.
Everyone has been telling me not to...

50:59.222 --> 51:00.598
- You are right.
- Don't you listen.

51:00.640 --> 51:02.975
Basically, I have been a loner my entire life.

51:03.060 --> 51:04.643
Well, sure, anyone can see that.

51:04.686 --> 51:07.772
You know, you're deep
and probably complicated.

51:08.690 --> 51:10.149
Can I buy you lunch?

51:10.233 --> 51:11.609
- Me?
- Please. Can I?

51:11.651 --> 51:12.818
Please. Look, I love... I love talking to you.

51:12.861 --> 51:13.986
Oh, uh, I was just going to go upstairs...

51:14.071 --> 51:15.821
- Don't, no, really, come on...
- Really?

51:15.864 --> 51:18.324
- I open myself up around you...
- Oh...

51:18.366 --> 51:19.825
Have you ever been to Hollywood?

51:19.868 --> 51:21.243
Uh, come on, no, of course not.

51:21.328 --> 51:23.871
You, well, I would
love to just take you around Hollywood.

51:23.955 --> 51:25.331
- I would real...
- Oh.

51:25.415 --> 51:26.999
- Could I make a confession?
- Sure.

51:27.042 --> 51:29.210
Look, my real name, it's not Gil Shepherd.

51:29.294 --> 51:31.629
- It's Herman Bardebedian.
- Really?

51:31.671 --> 51:35.132
I've, yeah, I've been a cab driver for about...

51:35.175 --> 51:37.968
- Boy, do you have a pretty face.
- Come on.

51:38.011 --> 51:39.678
- You do!
- Oh.

51:54.861 --> 51:56.529
EMMA: Hi, big boy.

51:58.573 --> 52:00.324
You alone?

52:00.367 --> 52:01.700
Oh, hello.

52:02.119 --> 52:06.664
Uh, well, I'm alone for now,
but later I have an appointment,

52:06.706 --> 52:08.833
or should I say rendezvous?

52:09.543 --> 52:11.001
Good for you.

52:11.711 --> 52:14.046
Where did you get the funny suit?

52:14.714 --> 52:16.882
- What, this?
- Yeah.

52:17.717 --> 52:19.718
You coming from a costume party?

52:19.803 --> 52:21.137
(LAUGHING)

52:21.805 --> 52:25.141
No, no, I'm Tom Baxter
of the Chicago Baxters.

52:25.225 --> 52:27.935
Explorer, poet, adventurer.
Just back from Cairo

52:28.019 --> 52:31.438
where I searched
in vain for the legendary purple rose.

52:32.232 --> 52:33.774
How about that?

52:34.192 --> 52:35.693
Well, uh, who are you?

52:35.735 --> 52:38.237
- My name's Emma.
- Oh, that's lovely.

52:38.280 --> 52:39.822
What do you do, Emma?

52:39.906 --> 52:41.574
I'm a working girl.

52:41.658 --> 52:43.993
And what do you do, you delicate creature?

52:44.077 --> 52:46.787
(CHUCKLING) Anything that'll make a buck.

52:47.706 --> 52:51.083
